Updated December 2016
DFA  VS.  VANGUARD VS.  ETF'S
Abstract:  Historical data on DFA asset class funds for limited time samples show DFA is likely adding 1% to 2% above committee designed indexes in most equity asset classes.  DFA creates additional returns by avoiding the costs bi-annual index reconstitution creates from forcing index trackers to buy or sell the same securities at the same time.  It also makes use of a variety of return enhancing strategies including the use of patient buying and selling strategies, dark pools, Instinet crosses, and stock lending.  ETF (Exchange Traded Fund) indexes are derivative securities with their own set of risks including premiums and discounts from the underlying securities and their tendency to trigger flash crashes in prices.

DFA's approach to portfolio construction and management is fundamentally different from other firms including those employing active management strategies as well as indexes and ETF's.  DFA uses academic research to define asset classes and structures portfolios to capture premiums, additional returns available when asset classes are tilted towards value and small cap stocks and globally diversified.  It also makes use of a variety of other return enhancing strategies.  Every 0.05% of additional return counts.  It is important to note that all passive and index strategies, whether DFA's, indexed mutual funds, or ETF's, have been shown to outperform active management strategies like stock picking and market timing and are almost always the better choice. See "Active and Passive Investment Strategy Comparison" elsewhere on our website.
DFA's asset class portfolios employ statistical analysis of long term data to define and differentiate asset classes and capture their returns.  While sometimes producing asset class returns similar to those from indexes the structure of DFA funds is passive and not based on committee designed indexes.  Indexed mutual funds and ETF's based upon indexes construct portfolios consisting of stocks or fixed income securities which are reviewed and modified by committees.  For example, the S&P 500 index measures the performance of large cap US growth stocks.  The S & P committee meets every six months, generally removes stocks which are doing poorly or fail to meet their criteria and replaces them with stocks which are considered a better fit for the index.  Coincidentially the replacements are often stocks with rising prices and that makes it a quasi-momentum fund.  In the 2008 bear market, for example, the S & P removed over 30 of the 500 stocks in the index.  During the tech/internet crash from early 2000 through end 2002 the NASDAQ 100 index removed over 80 stocks of the 100 stocks in the index.  Although the S & P and other indexes are generally referred to as benchmarks which active managers strive and usually fail to beat, they are more like a foot long ruler that is continually re-lengthened to make measurements look larger.  Benchmarks on benches do not move around.  The composition of indexes is not constant but a variable.
As opposed to committee designed indexes DFA structures portfolios to capture the returns in a well-defined asset class and includes every traded stock in a given asset class which passes its criteria for belonging in that asset class as defined by academic research.  DFA performs various common sense screens like eliminating companies with serious legal or regulatory problems or abnormal price behavior.  All securities in all portfolios are screened daily.  Criteria for asset class membership don't shift as a function of current opinion or committee decisions.  DFA determines the criteria for asset class membership based upon extensive statistical analysis of risk premiums.  Risk premiums are additional returns for additional volatility and risk in a given asset class.  Research by Fama and French and others indicates that the cost of capital for riskier ventures and thus the return to investors for providing that capital are likely to be higher for riskier assets that may be volatile in price or even fail, what's usually referred to as the risk/return trade off.
For equities, DFA identifies two main sources of premiums in U.S., international, and emerging markets.  They are the small cap premium and the value premium.  Historical data show that tilting towards value and small cap stocks in diversified portolios significantly increases returns over ever popular large cap growth and total stock market funds.  For U.S. markets, 1927 to 2007, the large value premium was about 3.5%, the small value premium was about 5.0%, and the small cap premium was about 2%.  For developed non-US markets, 1975 to 2007, the large value premium was about 4.5% and the small value premium was about 5%.  For emerging markets, 1989 to 2007, the value premium was about 4.5%.  Data is more limited for non-US markets but Dimson's study, "Triumph of the Optimists", covering 16 countries for 100 years, shows comparable value and small cap premiums in almost all countries.  It's annual updates for 1900 to 2015 show similar results.  DFA also incorporates momentum and profitability screens for all securities in its portfolios.
DFA  VS. VANGUARD
DFA's factor analytic based asset classes typically have significantly different portfolio compositions than indexes and index ETF's.  During December 2008 Vanguard's US large value index had a higher price/book ratio, 1.70, and higher average market cap, $43.5B, than DFA's US large value portfolio with a 1.30 price/book ratio and $23.1B average market cap.  A higher price/book indicates less capture of the value premium thus the DFA portfolio was more "valuey".  Asset classes go in and out of favor.  In 2008 Vanguard's large cap growth fund produced better returns, -35.97% versus DFA's -40.8%.  But for the trailing 10 year period, DFA's fund returned 2.15% per year versus 0.62% per year for Vanguard, a 153 annual basis point advantage for DFA.  During December 2008, Vanguard's US small value index had a price/book ratio of 1.30 and average market cap of $1.27B versus DFA's with a 1.10 price/book ratio and $0.676B average market cap.  For 2008, Vanguard's small cap value index lost 32.05% versus a larger loss of 36.79% for DFA but for the trailing 10 years DFA's US smalll cap value fund returned 7.32% versus Vanguard's return of 5.22%.  Through 2008 Vanguard's small cap US growth index returned 3.32% versus DFA's small cap return of 4.84% and DFA's US microcap return of 6.44%.  DFA specializes in capturing value and small cap premiums.
Seeking Alpha (October 2016) matched DFA and Vanguard funds by asset class for 1998 through May 2016 and found that DFA outperformed Vanguard by 0.1%, 1.4%, 1.2%, and 0.9% per year in US large cap, large value, small cap and small value asset classes respectively, net of expense ratios.  Vanguard only offers one index fund overseas, its total international stock fund, and it returned 3.9% annually for that period versus returns between 5.4% and 10.7% annually in DFA's various asset class portfolios in international developed and emerging markets.  We have done similar comparisons in the past and came up with an estimate that DFA strategies add somewhere between 1% and 2% annually to globally diversified equity portfolios.  This again highlights the importance of keeping advisory management fees as low as possible in DFA style portfolios.  It also suggests DFA's asset class portfolios are a bit more precise in capturing size and value premiums than committee designed indexes.
None of these comparisons are statistically robust since they are based on the very limited time frames sampled.  They do suggest that DFA's approach has added to returns in several equity asset classes.  DFA's 10 year trailing returns for their US large cap portfolio are near identical to Vanguard's and all other indexes tracking that asset class.  US large cap growth is very much a plain vanilla asset class available through at least one hundred different open-ended and index or ETF mutual funds.  But, that is not the case for most equity asset classes.  For example, through end-2007 the ten year trailing return for DFA's US large value fund was 6.11% versus the Russell large value index return of 4.42%.  DFA's US small value fund returned 9.62% versus 7.47% for the comparable Russell index.  DFA's international value fund returned 9.54% versus a return of 8.04% for the Russell index.  DFA's emerging markets value fund returned 22.22% versus 15.51% for the Russell emerging market index.
HOW DFA CREATES ADDITIONAL RETURNS VERSUS INDEXES AND ETF'S
DFA's additional returns arise from four factors.  The first is the factor analytic structure of their passive portfolios described above versus committee designed indexes.  The second is their avoidance of the cost of index reconstitutions.  Index based mutual funds and ETF's must promptly reconstitute portfolios every time index committees change index compositions.  This means pure index funds must buy and sell when everyone else running index funds does so, making for higher prices when buying and lower prices when selling.  DFA has examined index reconstitution in detail and finds that in day 49 after a change in index composition the cost of maintaining index portfolios subtracts over 60 basis points for US large value, over 120 basis points for US small caps, and 135 basis points for US small value.  A comprehensive study by Sunil Wahal examined all of DFA's equity trades from 2007 through 2009 and found its ability to be a liquidity provider when others were selling or buying generated a 60 to 80 basis point advantage in trading costs for DFA.
In addition to being a patient buyer and seller of securities and avoiding forced index tracking a third way DFA adds value is through extensive use of alternative trading markets like Instinet crossing and "dark pool" trading outside the conventional exchanges.  DFA is a patient slow buyer and seller of securities for all portfolios at all times.  A comprehensive study by Sunil Wahil examined all of DFA's equity trades from 2007 through 2009, over 1.3 million trades representing about $89 billion, and estimates DFA added 60 bps. to 80 bps. from reducing trading costs.The fourth way DFA creates additional returns versus indexes is from securities lending.  DFA is a major securities lender.  During fiscal year 2006, DFA's US securities lending added between 0 and 66 basis points to returns.
Often proponents of index mutual funds and ETF's promote their low fee structures.  While Vanguard and ETF based indexes do have slightly lower expense ratios for comparable asset classes DFA's funds are low cost and have far lower expense ratios than active funds.  Typically, the cost difference between DFA's funds and pure indexes or ETF's runs 10 to 25 basis points annually.  A common argument for ETF's is that they don't pass through yearly capital gains to investors since their structure is that of a derivative instrument.  Investors don't actually own shares, they own a number representing shares.  This argument has some merit though is often overemphasized.  ETF shares are derivative securities and not the same as directly owning shares.  DFA's funds typically pass through 1% to 2% or less of net asset value in capital gains each year, very low, and they've many tax-managed funds which reduce taxable pass-throughs even further.  All DFA, Vanguard, and ETF portfolios are very tax-efficient compared to actively managed portfolios.
POTENTIAL RISKS WITH ETF'S
ETF's are derivative securities with their own special characteristics and risks.  They are very different in structure from conventional open-ended mutual funds like those from DFA and Vanguard.  The purchasers of ETF's own shares in pledged assets where the share price can be above or below the actual market value of the shares.  Purchasers of ETF shares should be aware of the possibility that ETF's can trade at a substantial discount to the shares backing their net asset value (NAV) and thus don't accurately track the indexes and involve more share price volatility.  In theory, arbitrageurs will close the big spreads between share price and NAV if shares are priced under the NAV but a casual perusal of historical share price versus net asset value for ETF's reveals that many have traded at a 10% or 20% discount for months or years.  The Financial Times (5-24-14) notes that when market stress develops and investors need liquidity the most and wish to sell their ETF shares the authorized participants in ETF's who create the pledged shares are unlikely to close the gap by buying shares but will rather redeem their pledged shares to exit a losing position and leave ETF shareholders with shares worth less than the disappearing security pledges.
The New York Federal Reserve Bank, Wall Street's top regulator, announced in December 2014 that extreme price movements in ETF's holding stocks, bonds and other assets had prompted it to take a closer look at the inner workings of ETF's.  Nothing has been done as of late 2016.  The  ETF industry had about $3 trillion under managment as of Fall 2016.  The Fed is concerned that ETF share prices may not always reflect underlying asset values and that the authorized participants who create ETF shares might not do so if there are heavy redemption requests.
ETF's are not profitable for fund companies unless they hold $50 to $100 million or more in assets and thus many close when they can't raise sufficient assets.  During 2009 through 2010 about 140 shut down.  Hundreds of ETF's perform differently than the indexes they are supposed to track, sometimes strikingly so (WSJ, 10-10-10).  Their average tracking error versus the index was 1.25% in 2009.  Leveraged ETF's are even more problematic.  As of November 2010, all 52 leveraged ETF's that were operating since January 2008 had lost money according to Morningstar, even those where the underlying index rose.
And, ETF's are involved in speculative high frequency computer trading on Wall Street.  This was dramatically illustrated in the so-called "flash crash" on May 6, 2010 where the Dow fell almost 800 points in 25 minutes.  The Wall Street Journal reported that while the Dow lost as much as 9.2% temporarily many ETF's lost almost all their value, some dropping to pennies a share.  This is hardly the liquidity HFT proponents claim.  Many ETF's saw their net asset value fall only 8% to 9% while their share price plunged 60% or more, triggering stop losses far below where investors purchased the ETF's.  NASDAQ cancelled over 10000 trades that took place more than 60% below the pre-crash price.  When the damage was tallied about 70% of the cancelled trades during the flash crash involved ETF's (CBSMW, 11-21-10).  Thus, with indexes off around 10%, investors who were down 10% to 60% in ETF's lost significantly more than investors in conventional open-ended mutual funds if their stop losses were triggered.  One of the sales pitches for ETF's is that they allow intradday trading, unlike open-ended mutual funds.
The Wall Street Journal (10-3-12) carried an article entitled "ETF's Seen Moving Market as Tail Wags the Dog".  Sales of midcap stocks were driven by massive sales of midcap ETF's, producing a market where for just the fifth time in the last five years large and small cap indexes rose while midcaps declined on extraordinary volume.  They surmise that large ETF trades were influencing the prices of underlying securities, as opposed to the other way around, since securities prices are supposed to determine ETF prices.  This is another example of distortions introduced by ETF share prices departing from the quote prices of the underlying securities they represent.  For example, on June 20th 2013, a day where equity indexes declined substantially, the Financial Times reported, "The losses for ETF's today were far beyond what the most sophisticated financial risk models could have predicted for worst-case scenarios."  Illiquidity quickly became a problem.
On 7-25-13 the Financial Times reported that high levels of settlement failures on ETF's have revived a debate about their structure and liquidity.  Settlement failures occur when banks pledge assets to ETF's then fail to deliver them.  The Bank of International Settlements, the central bankers bank, had warned that settlement failures on ETF's pose potential systemic problems to the financial system.  Says one critic, "This is an unrealised operational risk which could morph into an actual operational risk in nanoseconds.  What is the actual liquidity of a security if it takes five days to find the security to make settlement?"  In May 2015 Reuters reported that the country's largest ETF providers are arranging billion dollar credit lines that can be tapped to keep illiquidity from turning an ETF sell-off into a credit market meltdown.  Vanguard Group, Guggenheim Investments and First Trust are among US fund companies that have lined up new or expanded bank guarantees.
On 12-12-16 and 12-13-16 the Financial Times reported that John Bogle, the founder of Vanguard funds, is calling on politicians to re-examine ETF's.  He complained that the annual turnover of securities in the biggest ETF that tracks the S&P 500 sometimes reach a stunning 3000% of assets.  He found that where mutual fund and ETF investors are invested in the same underlying fund, ETF investors trailed returns in conventional open ended funds by a large 1.6% annually.  He notes that the intraday market pricing in ETF's encourages trading (while prices in open ended funds are only set after the market close) and the evidence is clear that trading decreases returns.
On 2-1-16 the Financial Times published an article entitled, "Is it time to halt the rise of the ETF machine".  They note that on August 24th, 2015 more than a fifth of all US ETF's were forced to stop trading when the Dow Jones Industrial average dropped more than 1,100 points before rebounding.  Trading was littered with more than 1,000 halts that inhibited the essential arbitrage mechanisms of ETF's and prompted their prices to fall well below the indices they were designed to track.  Vanguard founder John Bogle has warned about ETF's even though Vanguard offers them, emphasizing their "sheer size and fragility in times of market stress".  The Financial Stability Board, set up after the 2008 financial crisis, said it had seen "a number of disquieting developments" in ETF's.  The Bank of England warned that the risks associated with ETF's are not being made clear.
ETF declines on August 24th, 2015 were again serious.  The US equity markets gapped down and major indexes declined 6% to 7% from their prior closing prices.  Many ETF's declined 10% to 35% with 220 ETF's declining at least 10%.  ETF liquidity disappeared instantly, thanks to high frequency trading computers, even though ETF's are supposed to track the underlying securities that have been pledged and enhance liquidity.  ETF providers immediately blamed rules put in place by NYSE Rule 48 after the May 2010 flash crash claiming they prevented accurate pricing of ETF's.  HFT traders said they did not have enough information to run their algorithms, backed out of the market, and withdrew liquidity.  The Dow plunged 1000 points to "reveal the structural limitations" underlying US equities.  Futures, cash and ETF's are priced and arbitraged off each other and according to the Financial Times HFT showed  "evidence of cracks in the plumbing that underpins the world's largest equity market."  Despite all the warnings from financial regulators and others no changes in ETF trading have been made as of late 2016.
A major marketing point promoted by the ETF industry is that they can be traded and stopped out any time during market hours.  But, during the May 2010 flash crash ETF investors were burned at the very moment they needed liquidity the most.  According to a Trim Tabs report ETF investors are so bad at picking the right time to buy or short-sell the equity markets that those doing exactly the opposite of what ETF investors did would have ended up with 700% profits.  Trim Tabs theorized that ETF's are mostly traded by less informed more emotional retail investors.  They believe the supposed liquidity of ETF's gives inexperienced investors a false sense of power.  DFA funds and index based mutual funds offered by Vanguard do not trade at a discount or premium to net asset value, cannot be shorted, and are only priced at market close.  EAM never recommends trading DFA funds, indexes or ETF's. This is discussed in "Tactical Asset Allocation" elsewhere on our website.
Another major marketing point of ETF's is their very low expense ratio.  Typically, ETF expense ratios run 10 to 15 basis points for fixed income and 15 to 30 basis points for equities but it varies depending upon asset classes and vendors.  Open-ended conventional mutual funds in passive and index funds from DFA and Vanguard typically run about 5 to 30 basis points above ETF's.  However, there is often a hidden additional cost to ETF's that is almost never mentioned.  ETF's are, in a sense, derivatives.  The shares they sell come from securities pledged to the ETF by other investment companies such as mutual funds.  When these companies lend the stock to ETF's there is some operational cost incurred for the share lender and that is ultimately passed on to the investor though we have been unable to determine what it is.  A Financial Times article (2-4-13) reported that US pension funds have sued Blackrock for "looting" securities lending revenues through creating an affiliate which profits from lending to Blackrock's US-listed iShares.
ETF's also engage in share lending.  ETFR (October 2010), the monthly publication of "Index Universe", reported that lending from ETF's is a practice shrouded in mystery and that obfuscation is the norm.  In any traded security obfuscation is not in the investor's interest.  ETFR notes that ETF's lend securities and collect money from that lending.  The borrower of the shares gives the ETF some form of collateral equal to the value of the loaned shares.  The ETF Company can then use that collateral, usually Treasuries or cash equivalents, to invest elsewhere.  Some of the profits from the invested collateral go to ETF shareholders and some to the ETF Company but it is highly variable.  They quote a leading securities law expert, "They don't want to talk about it because they don't want to disclose the extent to which they keep the proceeds."  ETFR notes, however, that the investment risk from proceeds rests entirely with the shareholders.  ETF lending exposes shareholders to counter party risk.  ETF companies differ greatly on their policies regarding lending and shareholder splits on fees. Vanguard gives investors 100% of their profits from lending, Wisdom Tree, 70%, and I-shares won't discuss its lending policies.
In summary, DFA's strategies, outlined above, aim to add value well above pure indexes and ETF's.  Although we always recommend and prefer DFA's offerings for equity allocations our philosophy at EAM is "candid but not dogmatic" and we sometimes mix DFA funds with Vanguard funds or ETF offerings if clients wish.












